{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_18","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Competitor Flow Research\n\nGenerated during active Fabro babysitting because the research fanout produced usable reference-pack data but did not materialize this exact required filename. This file is source-limited, contains no secrets, and should be superseded by richer agent research in future workflow runs.\n\n## Source List\n- competitor\n- competitor\n- competitor\n- competitor\n\n## References\n### Reference 1: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: onboarding\n- Tags: competitor, onboarding, sequence\n- What to adapt: Preserve deterministic onboarding sequencing but make it explicit and cancellable with a soft default path for first-run uncertainty.\n- What not to copy: Do not hard-lock users behind rigid first-run steps before they understand core value.\n\n### Reference 2: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: home\n- Tags: competitor, navigation, tabs\n- What to adapt: Keep a predictable tab model and strengthen labels to reduce ambiguity between task status and support/account lanes.\n- What not to copy: Do not over-conflate settings/support actions with core wake execution actions.\n\n### Reference 3: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: active_task\n- Tags: competitor, urgent_mode, mission_progress\n- What to adapt: Prioritize explicit active-task controls and immediate progress indication once a mission starts.\n- What not to copy: Do not overload the active screen with secondary decision links during wake mode.\n\n### Reference 4: competitor\n- Category: competitor_flow\n- Provider/source: competitor\n- Screen type: profile_settings\n- Tags: competitor, profile, settings\n- What to adapt: Use account/support sectioning with calmer hierarchy and clearer action grouping.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep operational and high-risk actions at the same visual weight or proximity.\n\n## Cross-Cutting Observations\n### Observation 1\n- What to adapt: Add explicit progress hints during first-run and a skip-safe path with safe defaults.\n- What not to copy: Do not force a strict linear sequence without recovery context.\n\n### Observation 2\n- What to adapt: Delay visual polish decisions that require pixel verification until screenshots are captured.\n- What not to copy: Do not claim validated visual quality where no evidence capture exists.\n\n### Observation 3\n- What to adapt: Add explicit fallback evidence tiering and mark inference-backed suggestions clearly in design docs.\n- What not to copy: Do not use invented competitor or review claims as if they were validated findings.\n\n### Observation 4\n- What to adapt: Strengthen wake-state surface for visible next step and state completion clarity.\n- What not to copy: Do not add hidden timers or non-explicit transitions in active wake mode.\n\n### Observation 5\n- What to adapt: Separate operational and accountability surfaces clearly in profile and home.\n- What not to copy: Do not keep critical wake controls mixed with legal/help actions.\n\n### Observation 6\n- What to adapt: Prioritize design changes with strong evidence in-app and defer uncertain behavior claims.\n- What not to copy: Do not overfit to unavailable external claims or unverified competitor patterns.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
