{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_27","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"mkdir -p .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions && cat > .workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/design/directions/calm_accountability_direction.md <<'EOF'\n# Design Direction: calm_accountability_direction\n## Target Emotion\n- First 10 seconds: grounded and in-control, with immediate clarity about today’s wake commitment.\n- Wake state: focused urgency without panic; one clear action and no visual noise.\n- After task completion: respected and steady; accountability is framed as continuity, not judgment.\n\n## Visual Principles\n- Layout density: medium-compact on home/list, low-density on active wake/completion to reduce decision load.\n- Contrast model: neutral surfaces with strong text contrast; urgency is signaled by hierarchy and state labels, not aggressive color floods.\n- Component shape language: iOS-native rounded rectangles and segmented groupings; avoid novelty containers that weaken scanning.\n- Information hierarchy: one primary CTA per screen, one supporting status line, secondary actions visually demoted.\n- Empty-state tone: instructional and calm (\\\"here is the next step\\\"), never guilt-coded.\n- Native iOS alignment: SF Symbols, large-title/list conventions, system sheets, standard tab behavior, predictable back/close affordances.\n\n## Colors And Tokens\n- Semantic tokens:\n  - \"'`color.bg.primary`, `color.bg.secondary`, `color.surface.card`\n  - `color.text.primary`, `color.text.secondary`, `color.text.muted`\n  - `color.action.primary`, `color.action.primaryPressed`, `color.action.secondary`\n  - `color.state.success`, `color.state.warning`, `color.state.destructive`, `color.state.disabled`\n  - `color.state.focusRing`, `color.state.highContrastBorder`\n- Light/dark behavior: hue-consistent tokens with luminance remapping per mode; do not swap semantic meaning between modes.\n- Accent strategy: single calm accent (blue-green family) reserved for commitment actions and progress confirmations.\n- Destructive states: red only for irreversible outcomes (delete task/account), not for missed wake messaging.\n- Success states: green for completion confirmation and repair completion; never accompanied by confetti/gamified pressure.\n- Disabled states: opacity + contrast-safe text fallback, not opacity alone.\n- High-contrast fallback: explicit border and text token overrides for WCAG-safe separations on cards/chips.\n\n## Typography\n- Dynamic Type: all text styles scale using semantic styles; no fixed-size text in action-critical surfaces.\n- Roles:\n  - Title: `.largeTitle`/`.title2` for wake intent and active-task headline.\n  - Body: `.body` for instructions and status.\n  - Caption/meta: `.footnote` for timing/context labels.\n- Numeric treatment: tabular numerals for timers, streak counts, and completion history values.\n- Minimum readable sizes: body-equivalent minimum 17pt in wake-critical areas; footnote never below 13pt equivalent.\n\n## Motion\n- Transition principles: quick orientation transitions, minimal decorative movement, clear state-change feedback.\n- Reduce Motion: replace scale/slide transitions with crossfade and static state swaps.\n- Haptics: soft impact on start/complete; warning haptic only for explicit failure states.\n- Timing ranges: 120-180ms tap feedback, 220-320ms state transitions, 0ms when Reduce Motion requires it.\n- Wake-state restraint: no looping attention animations during active wake; only one-time state acknowledgment.\n\n## Screen-By-Screen Implications\n- Onboarding: 3-step progressive setup (intent, default schedule, optional strictness) with visible skip-safe path and reversible defaults.\n- Home: top module is \"Next Wake Commitment\" with single primary action; metrics and history preview are secondary.\n- Primary list: group tasks by readiness (`Tonight`, `Later`, `Paused`), with clear status chips and low-friction resume.\n- Create/edit: sequence as `Intent -> Timing -> Safeguards -> Review`; avoid dumping advanced controls on first pane.\n- Active task: full focus surface with one dominant CTA, current-state banner, and a plainly labeled fallback action.\n- Completion: immediate confirmation, one suggested next step (log reflection or set next wake), plus optional repair guidance.\n- History/streaks: show reliability trend + \"why changed\" annotations; include one-tap repair planning after misses.\n- Profile/settings: separate Mission Controls, Account/Billing, and Help/Legal into distinct sections with different visual weight.\n- Paywall/subscription: premium framed as reliability tools and deeper insights, surfaced contextually after value moments, never blocking urgent wake flows.\n\n## Monetization Implications\n- Premium promise: stronger accountability tooling (advanced safeguards, deeper history insights, adaptive planning).\n- Must remain free: core wake flow, basic task creation/editing, completion logging, and non-coercive recovery actions.\n- Dark-pattern avoidance: no countdown pressure, forced trial walls in wake flow, deceptive close buttons, or shaming upsell copy.\n\n## Accessibility Risks\n- VoiceOver: risk of ambiguous status chips and action labels; require explicit state announcements and action verbs.\n- Dynamic Type: risk of clipped cards in home/list; enforce multiline-safe layouts and vertical growth.\n- Contrast: muted neutral palettes can underperform; require token-level contrast audits in both modes.\n- Reduced motion: animation-heavy progress transitions may confuse; provide clear non-motion state labels.\n- Haptics-only feedback: never rely on haptics as sole completion/failure signal.\n- Cognitive load: too many safeguards in active wake can create paralysis; progressive disclosure is required.\n- One-handed use: top-heavy controls in large phones can reduce completion reliability; keep primary wake CTA thumb-reachable.\n\n## Implementation Risks\n- SwiftUI complexity: tokenized theming + stateful wake surfaces can fragment if not centralized in a design-token layer.\n- Custom component risk: bespoke status chips/commitment cards may diverge from iOS behavior; keep wrappers around native primitives.\n- Animation risk: state transitions across active/completion/history can create race conditions with async task updates.\n- App Store risk: if paywall intrudes on core alarm/wake utility, review risk increases for deceptive gating.\n- Localization risk: calm microcopy may expand significantly in some languages; design for multiline and variable button widths.\n- Scope tradeoff: full reliability annotations in history may require backend/event model changes; phase rollout by surface.\n\n## Source List\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/design-opportunity-synthesis.md` - consolidated constraints, top-screen opportunities, and anti-patterns.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/competitor-flows.md` - competitor flow principles for sequencing and urgent-mode focus.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/pageflows-research.md` - pattern evidence for progressive onboarding and single-action active states.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/mobbin-mcp-research.md` - source-limited pattern guidance emphasizing adaptation-not-copy.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/apple-hig-research.md` - platform-aligned accessibility/interruption constraints.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/behavioral-ux-research.md` - calm vs urgent behavioral tone separation.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/app-store-review-mining.md` - hypothesis-only pain framing and evidence caution.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/preflight.json` - environment and evidence limitations affecting confidence.\n- `/home/daytona/workspace/.workflow/iphone-app-ux-studio/research/reference-gap-analysis.json` - confirms earlier evidence gaps and why conservative inference is necessary.\n\n## What To Adapt\n- Progressive setup with reversible defaults and explicit next-step framing.\n- Single-primary-action wake execution with persistent state clarity.\n- Recovery-first accountability language after misses.\n- Clear separation between mission-critical controls and account/legal surfaces.\n- Reliability explanations (why streak changed) over pure streak gamification.\n\n## What Not To Copy\n- Exact competitor, Mobbin, or PageFlows visual compositions, spacing systems, copy, iconography, or motion signatures.\n- Proprietary brand palettes, badges, reward metaphors, or onboarding scripts.\n- Punitive/shame-driven wake recovery patterns and coercive monetization sequences.\n- Any undocumented external claims presented as validated facts in this run.\n\n## No Secret Output\n- No credentials, tokens, private links, signed URLs, cookies, API keys, or user secrets were used or reproduced.\n- If encountered in source material: secret material omitted.\nEOF'","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
